<h2>Disability insurance at Wavetronix</h2>
<hr/>
<p>Wavetronix provides disability insurance to active full-time employees through MetLife. You are eligible for this insurance on the first of the month after the first full month of employment. So if you started on June 15, you&#39;d be eligible on August 1. The cost of this insurance to you (the premium, as it&#39;s called) is $3.25 per pay period. The rest of the cost of the insurance is covered by Wavetronix.</p>
<p>To have this insurance, you need to opt in during open enrollment, which happens toward the end of each calendar year. Additionally, you can make changes to your insurance at the time of a major life event, such as marriage or the birth of a child.</p>
<div class="spacer">&#160;</div>
<h2>Short term disability</h2>
<hr/>
<p>So you thought you could do that terrain park when you were skiing last week and now you&#39;re bedridden for a month until your back heals and you can stand again. What do you about work? For the first two calendar weeks (that is to say, ten business days), you use your paid time off. If you&#39;re still unable to work after that, short term disability kicks in on the 15<sup>th</sup> day after your accident or diagnosis.</p>
<p>For short term disability insurance to be applicable, your inability to work must be caused by accident or illness, and you may have to prove that you&#39;re genuinely unable to work via doctor&#39;s note or the like.</p>
<p>Short term disability will pay you 60% of what you would have been earning in a week, although they do put a cap on it: the maximum they will pay in a week is $1000. You can continue to receive this amount for 11 weeks; if at that point you&#39;re unable to return to work, you&#39;ll switch over to long term disability.</p>
<div class="spacer">&#160;</div>
<h2>Long term disability</h2>
<hr/>
<p>So you thought you could ignore the gates coming down and get across the tracks before the train came, and now you&#39;re in the hospital for the foreseeable future. What do you do about work? Once you&#39;ve passed your first two weeks of PTO and your eleven weeks of short term disability, long term disability kicks in. That is a total of 90 days between the injury and the beginning of your benefits. That 90-day wait is referred to as an elimination period.</p>
<p>Long term disability will pay you 60% of your monthly earnings, with a maximum of $6000. How long it lasts varies based on when the disabling event/diagnosis occurs. If you become disabled before the age of 60, the long term disability benefits will last until you turn 65. If you become disabled after the age of 60, the benefit period varies based on your age. For instance, if you become disabled at 62, you&#39;ll receive benefits for a further 42 months; if you become disabled at 67 (and haven&#39;t yet retired), you&#39;ll receive benefits for a further 18 months. For a full rundown of ages and benefits, see HR.</p>
<p>There&#39;s an exception to the above, however: there&#39;s a 24-month limit to the insurance if you&#39;re in outpatient care for mental illness or substance abuse. This means that if the thing making you unable to work is mental illness or substance abuse, and you&#39;re not hospitalized—the care you&#39;re receiving is, for instance, from a therapist you visit—the insurance will only pay benefits for two years. </p>
